{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611537"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16226"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16226"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.29,0.06,0.56,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66986"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8917"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16226"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52440"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1263"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22401"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66986"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGynaecomastia is a benign enlargement of male breast tissue that can occur due to various hormonal imbalances (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological appearance of gynaecomastia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adipose tissue hyperplasia only","Lobular proliferation with terminal duct formation","Atypical ductal hyperplasia with calcification","Ductal and stromal proliferation without lobule formation","Inflammatory cell infiltration with fibrosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological hallmark of gynaecomastia is \u003Cstrong\u003Eductal and stromal proliferation without lobule formation\u003C/strong\u003E. This includes an increase in ductal epithelium surrounded by loose, fibrous stroma. The ducts may show mild epithelial hyperplasia but remain benign in appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELobular proliferation with terminal duct formation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of female breast tissue development but does not occur in gynaecomastia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdipose tissue hyperplasia only\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes pseudogynaecomastia, which is different from true gynaecomastia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory cell infiltration with fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - While some fibrosis may be present in long-standing cases, inflammation is not a primary feature\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical ductal hyperplasia with calcification\u003C/strong\u003E - These changes are more commonly associated with malignant processes and are not typical of gynaecomastia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe histological changes in gynaecomastia reflect the underlying hormonal stimulation of male breast tissue, particularly the effect of increased oestrogen action relative to androgens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gynaecomastia shows ductal proliferation and periductal stromal proliferation on histology without lobule formation.","True gynaecomastia is distinct from pseudogynaecomastia which shows only increased adipose tissue without ductal changes."],"references":["Johnson RE, Murad MH. Gynecomastia: pathophysiology, evaluation, and management. Mayo Clin Proc. 2009 Nov;84(11):1010-5. doi: 10.1016/S0025-6196(11)60671-X. PMID: 19880691; PMCID: PMC2770912.","Cuhaci N, Polat SB, Evranos B, Ersoy R, Cakir B. Gynecomastia: Clinical evaluation and management. Indian J Endocrinol Metab. 2014 Mar;18(2):150-8. doi: 10.4103/2230-8210.129104. PMID: 24741509; PMCID: PMC3987263.","Fagerlund A, Lewin R, Rufolo G, Elander A, Santanelli di Pompeo F, Selvaggi G. Gynecomastia: A systematic review. J Plast Surg Hand Surg. 2015;49(6):311-8. doi: 10.3109/2000656X.2015.1053398. Epub 2015 Jun 7. PMID: 26051284.","Narula HS, Carlson HE. Gynaecomastia--pathophysiology, diagnosis and treatment. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2014 Nov;10(11):684-98. doi: 10.1038/nrendo.2014.139. Epub 2014 Aug 12. PMID: 25112235."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52440"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16226"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21282"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21282"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BzSa86nYHE11EXeInTVU2DA2FnjEfm.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/BzSa86nYHE11EXeInTVU2DA2FnjEfm.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":317,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52440"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T09:41:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T09:41:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8917"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66986"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https: